00:39:15,820 --> 00:39:17,054
He didn't believe in it.

471
00:39:17,488 --> 00:39:19,790
You know, God had an argument with him.

472
00:39:20,091 --> 00:39:27,498
According to Midrashic interpretation,
a full week God spent arguing with

473
00:39:27,498 --> 00:39:32,903
Moses to convince him that those
slaves, insensitive slaves, who took

474
00:39:32,903 --> 00:39:38,809
everything for granted, are worthy
of liberation, and those slaves will

475
00:39:38,809 --> 00:39:44,849
turn into a great mamlechet kohanim,
into a kingdom of priests.

476
00:39:44,849 --> 00:39:47,351
The whole situation was bewildering.

477
00:39:47,351 --> 00:39:50,154
Yes, Moses broke the silence.

478
00:39:50,154 --> 00:39:55,926
He began to move toward the
living, speaking center; however,

479
00:39:55,926 --> 00:39:58,195
the word was still missing.

480
00:39:58,796 --> 00:40:03,267
The logos of need was
not revealed to Moses.

481
00:40:03,534 --> 00:40:10,241
And that revelation took place
when Moses reached Mount Sinai.

482
00:40:10,875 --> 00:40:16,180
Then, he understood the meaning
of liberation, and he also

483
00:40:16,180 --> 00:40:20,418
understood his people, that his
people are a very funny group.

484
00:40:20,985 --> 00:40:26,957
They can rise from a

485
00:40:26,957 --> 00:40:34,832
silent existence to an existence
full of sound and song and

486
00:40:34,832 --> 00:40:40,104
speech within seven weeks.

487
00:40:42,807 --> 00:40:50,114
They can fall into a bottomless
abyss quickly, but they can

488
00:40:50,114 --> 00:40:53,184
rise to the stars suddenly.

489
00:40:53,818 --> 00:40:55,419
That Moses understood

490
00:40:55,419 --> 00:40:56,887
at Mount Sinai.

491
00:40:58,322 --> 00:41:02,293
And then, the word was bestowed upon

492
00:41:02,293 --> 00:41:06,697
him, the greatest gift
that God bestows upon man.

493
00:41:12,903 --> 00:41:16,740
Now, let me continue if you
are not tired to listen.

494
00:41:17,842 --> 00:41:19,276
Slavery

495
00:41:20,211 --> 00:41:23,747
is not only a political,
juridic institution.

496
00:41:25,149 --> 00:41:27,451
It's not only a political,
juridic reality.

497
00:41:28,519 --> 00:41:29,386
It's more than that.

498
00:41:31,522 --> 00:41:36,427
It is even more than a
psychological reality.

499
00:41:38,896 --> 00:41:43,200
Slavery, or bondage, is
an existential reality.

500
00:41:45,135 --> 00:41:48,372
I would say, a modus essendi.

501
00:41:48,372 --> 00:41:51,809
It's a way of life.

502
00:41:54,211 --> 00:41:58,415
You'll ask me -- and certainly, you would

503
00:41:58,415 --> 00:42:05,422
ask me if you wanted to interrupt
me -- how does existential

504
00:42:05,422 --> 00:42:07,791
slavery express itself?

505
00:42:07,791 --> 00:42:11,562
We know how juridic, political
slavery expresses itself.

506
00:42:11,562 --> 00:42:12,463
We know that.

507
00:42:13,531 --> 00:42:18,335
But how does existential slavery
demonstrate itself, manifest itself?

508
00:42:18,335 --> 00:42:19,270
How?

509
00:42:19,270 --> 00:42:19,870
What is it?

510
00:42:19,870 --> 00:42:21,872
What kind of an existence is it?

511
00:42:24,174 --> 00:42:25,910
I'll answer you immediately.

512
00:42:25,910 --> 00:42:30,147
In a peripheral existence.

513
00:42:30,147 --> 00:42:33,517
If a person leads a peripheral
existence,  

514
00:42:36,820 --> 00:42:39,757
he is a slave existentially.

515
00:42:40,190 --> 00:42:50,301
I'll tell you – I mean, luckily, I'm a
rabbi, as Dr. Levin told you, I'm a rav.

516
00:42:50,868 --> 00:42:55,105
Unfortunately – not unfortunately,
gratefully – there was a secular

517
00:42:55,105 --> 00:43:02,079
Jewish writer who described the
existential slave in a beautiful manner.

518
00:43:02,446 --> 00:43:09,987
I could have picked other quotations
from other writers, but I believe

519
00:43:09,987 --> 00:43:12,389
he did it in a magnificent fashion.

520
00:43:13,057 --> 00:43:14,358
This is Peretz.

521
00:43:14,358 --> 00:43:16,293
We all know the story of 
Bontshe Shvayg.

522
00:43:16,293 --> 00:43:17,595
Many of you know.

523
00:43:17,595 --> 00:43:19,563
I don't know how many know.

524
00:43:19,563 --> 00:43:22,099
If I were in my class, I would
tell you raise your hand, right?

525
00:43:22,866 --> 00:43:25,402
Not those who know, those who don't know.

526
00:43:26,937 --> 00:43:29,206
But there is

527
00:43:30,407 --> 00:43:32,610
just at the beginning.

528
00:43:32,610 --> 00:43:34,144
The whole story I don't like.

529
00:43:34,878 --> 00:43:36,847
It's too sarcastic.

530
00:43:36,847 --> 00:43:38,415
It's even cynical.

531
00:43:38,983 --> 00:43:43,320
However, the description of Bontshe
Shvayg -- the name itself, shvayg,

532
00:43:43,320 --> 00:43:46,256
means silence -- is beautiful.

533
00:43:47,291 --> 00:43:51,762
Shall I read the beginning in Yiddish or
you want me to give you the translation?

534
00:43:51,762 --> 00:43:52,429
In Yiddish.

535
00:43:52,429 --> 00:43:53,964
Yiddish in the beginning,
all right, I understand.

536
00:43:53,964 --> 00:44:01,305
Peretz starts with the following
paragraph: "Da oyf der velt hot Bontshe

537
00:44:01,305 --> 00:44:04,541
Shvayg's toyt gor keyn ayndruk gemakht.

538
00:44:05,409 --> 00:44:09,913
Fregt imatsen becherem ver Bontshe Shvayg iz geven.

539
00:44:10,581 --> 00:44:14,652
Bontshe hot shtil gelebt un iz shtil geshtorbn; 

540
00:44:14,652 --> 00:44:17,888
vi a shotn iz er durkh gegangen undzer velt.

541
00:44:18,822 --> 00:44:24,595
Oyf Bontshe's bris hot men keyn vayn
nisht getrunken, es hobn keyn koyses

542
00:44:24,595 --> 00:44:29,933
geklungen, tsu bar mitzveh hot er
keyn klingendike droshe nisht gezogt.

543
00:44:29,933 --> 00:44:35,873
Gelebt hot er vi a groy kleyn
kerndl zamd baym breg fun

544
00:44:35,873 --> 00:44:39,443
yam, tsvishn milyonen zayns glaykhn.

545
00:44:39,943 --> 00:44:43,881
Az der vint hot'n oyfgehoybn un
oyf der anderer zayt yam

546
00:44:43,881 --> 00:44:46,684
aribergeyogt hot es
keyner nisht bamertkt."

547
00:44:47,751 --> 00:44:50,220
Now, it's my translation, I wanted to say.

548
00:44:50,220 --> 00:44:54,591
Find fault, find it with me, not
with Peretz: Bontshe Shvayg's death

549
00:44:54,591 --> 00:44:57,995
made no impression whatsoever.

550
00:44:57,995 --> 00:45:00,998
No one knew who Bontshe was.

551
00:45:01,498 --> 00:45:04,968
Bontshe lived mutely and died quietly.

552
00:45:05,703 --> 00:45:09,740
Like a silent shadow, he
did pass through our world.

553
00:45:10,374 --> 00:45:18,549
At Bontshe's circumcision, no toasts
were raised, no glasses were clinked.

554
00:45:18,549 --> 00:45:22,853
At bar mitzvah, no rousing
speech was delivered.

555
00:45:22,853 --> 00:45:29,827
He lived in anonymity like a
gray, minute grain of sand on the

556
00:45:29,827 --> 00:45:35,666
beach of a stormy sea, among
millions of identical sand particles.

557
00:45:36,033 --> 00:45:37,701
No one noticed

558
00:45:37,701 --> 00:45:45,576
that one of the particles was picked up by
the storm wind and carried far, far away.

559
00:45:45,576 --> 00:45:49,780
[Inaudible]

560
00:45:50,814 --> 00:45:54,918
They are slaves, not in a juridic fashion

561
00:45:54,918 --> 00:45:57,454
but in an existential sense.

562
00:45:57,454 --> 00:46:00,390
They are faceless; they are nameless.

563
00:46:01,892 --> 00:46:04,161
No one is interested in them.

564
00:46:05,028 --> 00:46:10,601
No one is concerned with or about them.

565
00:46:10,601 --> 00:46:18,008
No one rejoices in their presence,
and no one bemoans their absence.

566
00:46:18,942 --> 00:46:25,349
They come and go like Peretz's
Bontshe Shvayg without leaving

567
00:46:25,349 --> 00:46:28,285
a trace, without making a mark.

568
00:46:28,786 --> 00:46:31,021
They are forgotten people.

569
00:46:31,255 --> 00:46:33,457
The cemeteries are full of them.

570
00:46:34,792 --> 00:46:43,567
The death notice and the obituary page
in a paper, if such a notice did appear,

571
00:46:44,268 --> 00:46:50,340
or the inscription on the tombstone,
is the only reminder that somebody

572
00:46:50,340 --> 00:46:55,078
existed somewhere, sometime ago.

573
00:47:00,517 --> 00:47:06,924
Those people lack, like the slave
of antiquity, a "need" awareness.

574
00:47:07,691 --> 00:47:10,527
They know not what suffering is.

575
00:47:11,261 --> 00:47:12,729
They are, therefore, speechless.

576
00:47:13,330 --> 00:47:14,898
They are even voiceless.

577
00:47:15,999 --> 00:47:20,337
Man was endowed with voice
and speech in order to react.

578
00:47:20,337 --> 00:47:24,942
God gave him speech and voice in
order to react in a human fashion

579
00:47:24,942 --> 00:47:29,646
to suffering, in order to be able
to define and articulate his needs.

580
00:47:30,380 --> 00:47:35,052
With the disappearance of
a "need" awareness, one

581
00:47:35,052 --> 00:47:38,889
forfeits voice and speech as well.

582
00:47:42,025 --> 00:47:43,827
But let me add something.

583
00:47:44,928 --> 00:47:51,568
We have been speaking about some
people, like Bontshe Shvayg, who

584
00:47:51,568 --> 00:47:55,339
lead a peripheral, silent existence.

585
00:47:55,339 --> 00:47:56,607
This is not true.

586
00:47:56,840 --> 00:48:01,945
May I use this term, Judaic
existentialism, because the oldest

587
00:48:01,945 --> 00:48:08,685
book on existentialism is not Pascal
or Augustine but the Tehillim.

588
00:48:09,753 --> 00:48:13,657
This is the oldest book on existentialism.

589
00:48:13,657 --> 00:48:18,996
To attribute existentialism to
Augustine or to Pascal or to

590
00:48:18,996 --> 00:48:22,666
Kierkegaard is simply plagiarism.

591
00:48:24,001 --> 00:48:26,203
They all plagiarized the Tehillim.

592
00:48:28,772 --> 00:48:36,113
Judaic existentialism has 
gone a step further.

593
00:48:36,914 --> 00:48:44,554
It has frankly stated that not some of
the people lead a silent or peripheral

594
00:48:44,554 --> 00:48:48,492
existence, they are bondsmen, slaves.

595
00:48:48,492 --> 00:48:51,962
 This is true, but it's not the full truth. 

596
00:48:52,362 --> 00:48:54,765
Judaism has frankly stated that

597
00:48:54,765 --> 00:49:03,273
all the people are existentially
peripheral, mute beings, fringe dwellers.

598
00:49:05,242 --> 00:49:10,213
no matter how vocal and
no matter how energetic they are.

599
00:49:12,082 --> 00:49:18,655
When the Ecclesiastes said, "Ki
ba'choshech ba u'va'choshech

600
00:49:18,655 --> 00:49:22,893
yelech u'va'choshech shemo
yechuseh," for it comes

601
00:49:22,893 --> 00:49:29,566
in vanity, and departs in darkness, and
the name thereof is covered with darkness.

602
00:49:30,167 --> 00:49:39,609
He did not refer only to the timid soul,
to the poor and meek, the Bontshe Shvaygs,

603
00:49:39,609 --> 00:49:44,481
but to everybody, to the great ruler,
to the daring warrior, to the captain

604
00:49:44,481 --> 00:49:47,417
of industry, and to the famous orator.

605
00:49:48,251 --> 00:49:56,560
No matter how prestigious an
existence he lives in his terms,

606
00:49:57,928 --> 00:50:01,465
he lives on the outskirts of being.

607
00:50:07,938 --> 00:50:12,209
We have developed before the
equation of silence and the

608
00:50:12,209 --> 00:50:15,112
absence of a "need" awareness.

609
00:50:15,412 --> 00:50:19,816
Judaism holds the view that no
individual has a right to boast that

610
00:50:19,816 --> 00:50:25,355
he possesses the right sensitivity
to and knowledge of his needs.

611
00:50:26,289 --> 00:50:30,594
Not even the most sophisticated
and the most enlightened person is

612
00:50:30,594 --> 00:50:33,230
familiar with his genuine needs.

613
00:50:33,230 --> 00:50:37,034
In fact, man is totally
ignorant, even of his most

614
00:50:37,034 --> 00:50:41,838
cardinal needs, urges, and desires.

615
00:50:43,106 --> 00:50:48,812
And here comes in a very strange
philosophical doctrine which plays

616
00:50:48,812 --> 00:50:50,447
an important role in Judaism.

617
00:50:51,481 --> 00:50:57,320
The double image doctrine, which plays
such a significant role in our philosophy

618
00:50:57,320 --> 00:51:03,360
of sin and repentance, lies at the very
root of our pessimistic appraisal of

619
00:51:03,360 --> 00:51:06,263
man's relationship to his own needs.

620
00:51:07,397 --> 00:51:11,668
Sin in Judaism -- what I mean by the
double image theory is as follows.

621
00:51:11,668 --> 00:51:18,942
Sin in Judaism, in contradistinction to
Christian theology since Augustine, is

622
00:51:18,942 --> 00:51:22,379
not within man but extraneous to man.

623
00:51:22,379 --> 00:51:24,381
It's something foreign to man.

624
00:51:25,582 --> 00:51:32,389
The cause of sin is to be found
not in man, not in genuine man, but

625
00:51:32,389 --> 00:51:36,860
in the identification of man with
the wrong image,

626
00:51:37,260 --> 00:51:43,867
with a phony “I” awareness.

627
00:51:46,269 --> 00:51:51,007
If man identifies himself with
a pseudo, with the pseudo “I”,

628
00:51:51,508 --> 00:51:58,281
with a phony “I” awareness, then
that identification breeds sin.

629
00:51:59,649 --> 00:52:01,751
What is repentance according to Judaism?

630
00:52:01,751 --> 00:52:05,522
Maimonides formulated it in one sentence.

631
00:52:05,522 --> 00:52:10,026
Repentance is the consequence
of rediscovery of the genuine

632
00:52:10,026 --> 00:52:12,629
“I”, of the genuine image,

633
00:52:14,364 --> 00:52:17,400
and sin means the wrong identification. 

634
00:52:18,802 --> 00:52:20,971
Now, let us draw a very simple

635
00:52:20,971 --> 00:52:27,844
conclusion. If Man has a tendency to
identify himself with the wrong “I”

636
00:52:27,844 --> 00:52:36,987
personality, then he'll also want to
respond to the needs of that personality.

637
00:52:37,787 --> 00:52:40,090
We are very ambitious.

638
00:52:40,090 --> 00:52:44,394
As a matter of fact, modern
man has countless needs,

639
00:52:45,228 --> 00:52:46,930
but they don't belong to him.

640
00:52:47,697 --> 00:52:50,634
They are needs of somebody else.

641
00:52:54,771 --> 00:53:01,111
In a word, not only some people live
on the periphery, but all of us.

642
00:53:01,845 --> 00:53:08,218
Man, with the wrong table of
needs is not a full being.

643
00:53:12,222 --> 00:53:17,961
And at this point, another Judaic
doctrine comes to the fore,

644
00:53:17,961 --> 00:53:20,997
namely the activist doctrine.

645
00:53:20,997 --> 00:53:24,701
Activist is probably a very fashionable
word among the Russian Jews who

646
00:53:24,701 --> 00:53:29,039
call them -- those who stand up
and speak are called activists.

647
00:53:29,039 --> 00:53:33,944
But it is a Judaic activist
doctrine of self-redemption.

648
00:53:38,114 --> 00:53:39,716
What does this doctrine say?

649
00:53:39,716 --> 00:53:43,520
Maimonides, in my opinion – I don't know
whether some historians will agree with me

650
00:53:43,520 --> 00:53:47,724
or not – in my opinion, this is a central
doctrine in Maimonides' Moreh Nevuchim.

651
00:53:47,991 --> 00:53:51,828
It comes to expression, unfortunately,
not in this first part, and not in

652
00:53:51,828 --> 00:53:53,830
the middle part, but in the last part.

653
00:53:53,830 --> 00:53:56,099
Usually, historians forget
about the last part.

654
00:53:56,600 --> 00:54:00,704
The story is about the Alshich, an
old Jew said that he became a heretic,

655
00:54:00,704 --> 00:54:02,272
an apikores, because of the Alshich.

656
00:54:02,272 --> 00:54:07,777
Because the Alshich has the habit of
formulating maybe 20, 25 questions, and

657
00:54:07,777 --> 00:54:09,746
then he begins to resolve the questions.

658
00:54:09,746 --> 00:54:12,282
It was Shabbos, and the Jew
was tired after the meal.

659
00:54:12,282 --> 00:54:16,586
So, the questions he did read,
but the answers, by the time he

660
00:54:16,586 --> 00:54:20,357
was supposed to read the answers,
he was asleep, sound asleep.

661
00:54:20,657 --> 00:54:24,628
So, he was -- after a certain
period of time, he found himself

662
00:54:24,628 --> 00:54:27,063
full of questions without answers.

663
00:54:27,063 --> 00:54:30,000
This is the trouble with
Maimonides, that actually this

664
00:54:30,000 --> 00:54:33,937
theory was expounded by Maimonides

665
00:54:33,937 --> 00:54:36,940
in the third section of Moreh Nevuchim.

666
00:54:37,807 --> 00:54:39,809
What does this theory say?

667
00:54:41,211 --> 00:54:45,048
I believe this doctrine says as follows.

668
00:54:45,048 --> 00:54:52,455
Man comes into our world as a hyletic – I
mean, I'm using the Aristotelian jargon,

669
00:54:52,455 --> 00:54:54,824
but I don't have a better word for that.

670
00:54:54,824 --> 00:55:00,163
It means what we call in our
traditional medieval philosophical

671
00:55:00,163 --> 00:55:01,798
jargon, chomer hiyuli.

672
00:55:01,798 --> 00:55:03,566
I mean, some people heard it.

673
00:55:03,566 --> 00:55:07,804
Chomer hiyuli means there is
potency, but there is no actuality.

674
00:55:07,804 --> 00:55:10,140
It's called hyle in Greek.

675
00:55:10,874 --> 00:55:15,845
He comes as a hyletic, 
amorphous being.

676
00:55:17,814 --> 00:55:21,484
He is created, of course,
in the image of God.

677
00:55:21,951 --> 00:55:31,328
However, this image is a
challenge, is an idea, or

678
00:55:31,328 --> 00:55:34,464
I would rather say it's an ideal.

679
00:55:34,464 --> 00:55:39,102
It's a twinkling star on a far horizon.

680
00:55:40,003 --> 00:55:44,674
It is not a grant, a gratuitous grant, but

681
00:55:44,674 --> 00:55:49,346
God gives man the divine
image just for the asking.

682
00:55:51,014 --> 00:55:58,621
It is up to man to take an ideal and
translate it into a reality; to reach

683
00:55:58,621 --> 00:56:04,561
out for the twinkling star, no matter
how distant man is from that star.

684
00:56:05,762 --> 00:56:09,833
It's up to man to objectify himself,

685
00:56:10,700 --> 00:56:18,875
to impress form upon a latent, formless,
even though a divine personality, and to

686
00:56:18,875 --> 00:56:30,186
move from the hyletic, silent periphery to
the center of objective, formed reality.

687
00:56:31,354 --> 00:56:34,324
This is basically the idea,
according to Maimonides.

688
00:56:34,324 --> 00:56:37,861
I don't have to tell you that, 
the ideal of education.

689
00:56:40,430 --> 00:56:47,570
The highest norm in Maimonidean
moral code is rather strange.

690
00:56:47,570 --> 00:56:48,605
What would you say?

691
00:56:49,172 --> 00:56:50,140
What would you say?

692
00:56:50,940 --> 00:56:52,375
What would you say?

693
00:56:52,375 --> 00:56:53,843
I mean, knowing Maimonides,

694
00:56:55,478 --> 00:56:57,714
what does he consider
the highest moral norm?

695
00:56:58,681 --> 00:57:00,283
A very short norm.

696
00:57:00,650 --> 00:57:02,552
To be.

697
00:57:03,453 --> 00:57:04,254
To exist.

698
00:57:04,954 --> 00:57:05,989
Maimonides did

699
00:57:05,989 --> 00:57:09,325
not have Hamlet's doubts
whether to be or not to be.

700
00:57:12,128 --> 00:57:17,000
If it is to be, it means play, to exist.

701
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:20,336
But to exist, in Maimonides, means

702
00:57:20,336 --> 00:57:27,644
